        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Leo, the strongest counterargument: do not build “comprehensive system prompts.” That becomes an opaque precedence engine with irreproducible behavior. Build a versioned prompt compiler, immutable execution snapshots, and a prompt receipt. Confidence: high.\n\n### Research verdict\n\n| Project | Useful pattern | Do not copy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Codex | Per-model prompt catalog; global and project `AGENTS.md`; distinct system/developer/user layers. | On model switches, it retains the old thread base and layers the new prompt inside `<model_switch>`, creating duplication and conflict risk. [Source](https://github.com/openai/codex/tree/56395bddaf26eb2829387ca6a417bf9128e5b239) |\n| Claude Code | Managed/user/project/local instruction scopes; explicit append-versus-replace system prompt APIs; visible model switching. `CLAUDE.md` is lower-authority user context, not security policy. [Memory docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/memory), [model switching](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/model-config) | Treating behavioral Markdown as enforcement. The exact leaked `<system-reminder>` is implementation detail, not a contract. |\n| OpenCode | Rebuilds prompt context per request; discovers nested instructions; sanitizes provider-specific history when switching models. [Prompt composition](https://github.com/anomalyco/opencode/blob/fab213312927ea64cf968832c527206e8c944f9e/packages/opencode/src/session/llm/request.ts#L56-L112) | Model-family selection through model-name substring matching; silent full replacement through `agent.prompt`. |\n| OpenClaw | Strongest architecture: deterministic sections, stable/dynamic cache boundary, semantic `AGENTS.md`/`SOUL.md`/`USER.md`, rebuilt prompts per fallback attempt, structured fallback events, `/context` diagnostics. [System prompt](https://docs.openclaw.ai/concepts/system-prompt), [failover](https://docs.openclaw.ai/concepts/model-failover) | Duplicated budget constants and too many source types without a sufficiently strict authority model. |\n| Prompt leaks repo | Useful historical diff and hypothesis catalog. | Not authoritative. It mixes captured prompts, published vendor prompts, inferred behavior, and account-specific artifacts. The Claude model-switch reminder is only moderate-confidence secondary evidence. [Snapshot](https://github.com/asgeirtj/system_prompts_leaks/blob/c685a36090c69d7aeb3744106b4d396fcf7c08f8/Anthropic/Claude%20Code/injected-reminders/model-switched.md#L1) |\n\nPinned revisions: Codex `56395bd`, OpenCode `fab2133`, OpenClaw `347ee45`, Claude Code `07dcb0e`, leaks `7882386`.\n\n### llame’s current gap\n\nllame currently has:\n\n- One hardcoded prompt in [context-builder.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/api/src/chats/context-builder.ts:230).\n- That prompt compiled at execution time in [run-execution.service.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/api/src/runs/run-execution.service.ts:307).\n- Only `modelId` persisted on the run in [chats.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/api/src/db/schema/chats.ts:261).\n- Per-message model information already exposed through [message-usage.tsx](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/web/app/(chat)/components/message-usage.tsx:218).\n\nThat is insufficient for reproducibility. A queued run can retain its model ID while silently receiving changed model configuration, prompt text, admin instructions, or fallback policy.\n\n### Architecture direction\n\nUse a typed `PromptPlan` with these authority layers:\n\n1. **Runtime kernel** — llame-owned, non-replaceable, security/tool invariants.\n2. **Product model profile** — versioned by capability family, with exact-model overrides.\n3. **Instance layer** — administrator global extension plus per-model append or explicit replacement.\n4. **User behavior** — `SOUL`-like persona and preferences.\n5. **User profile** — `USER`-like factual context, explicitly not behavioral authority.\n6. **Workspace/project instructions** — `AGENTS`-like operating context if llame projects gain this scope.\n7. **Runtime suffix** — model identity, environment, compaction facts, and necessary transition context.\n\nEach fragment needs source, owner, role, revision, hash, token count, truncation status, stability class, and visibility policy. The provider adapter may flatten this to a string, but the internal representation must remain structured.\n\nFor every generation, persist a content-addressed `PromptSnapshot` plus:\n\n- requested model;\n- actual model;\n- fallback reason and attempted chain;\n- provider/model profile revision;\n- prompt and tool-schema hashes;\n- source revisions and truncation;\n- compiler/renderer version.\n\nOn model switch:\n\n- Persist a structured timeline event.\n- Recompile the target model’s own profile.\n- Preserve the frozen user/admin source revisions unless explicitly reloaded.\n- Strip incompatible provider-native reasoning/tool metadata.\n- Inject an ephemeral developer reminder only when the behavior or capability contract materially changed.\n- Never render literal `<system-reminder>` markup as a chat message.\n\nFor fallback:\n\n- Retry only before visible output or tool side effects.\n- Resolve the fallback model’s own profile.\n- Track selected and actual model separately.\n- Never silently fallback on context overflow, refusal, user abort, tool failure, or application bugs.\n- Surface one transition notice, then keep the normal UI quiet.\n\nThe UX should have three levels:\n\n1. Per-message actual-model chip and one-time switch/fallback boundary.\n2. “Prompt receipt” showing ordered layers, revisions, sizes, and provenance.\n3. Advanced effective-prompt inspector with diffs, fallback attempts, role mapping, and truncation details.\n\nThis preserves the stable prompt prefix for provider caching while keeping runtime facts at the end, matching both OpenAI and Anthropic caching guidance. [OpenAI caching](https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/prompt-caching), [Anthropic caching](https://platform.claude.com/docs/en/build-with-claude/prompt-caching).\n\nOne decision blocks the final design:\n\n**Should authenticated users be able to inspect the full llame-owned effective prompt for every turn—including administrator extensions—or may administrators hide instruction text and expose only its label, revision, and hash?**\n\nMy recommendation: full visibility. Hidden administrator prompts are not a security boundary; they undermine llame’s transparency goal. Provider-owned instructions outside llame can be marked unavailable because llame genuinely cannot disclose them.\n\nNo repository files changed.\n\n<oai-mem-citation>\n<citation_entries>\nMEMORY.md:260-283|note=[located prior llame model catalog and selected model persistence work]\nrollout_summaries/2026-07-08T20-36-08-AriI-models_endpoint_available_models_openspec_self_test.md:42-69|note=[reused prior model selection and execution wiring context]\n</citation_entries>\n<rollout_ids>\n019f4371-f1a5-7922-838d-530f1bd20ec4\n</rollout_ids>\n</oai-mem-citation>",
