        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Leo, the cleanest MVP is narrower than the previous design: full per-model prompts, immutable prompt receipts, and model-transition events. No user customization layers yet.\n\nOne correction: do not duplicate tool descriptions inside the system prompt. Structured tool schemas already carry descriptions. The per-model prompt should define tool-use behavior—when to search, how to treat retrieved content—not maintain a second copy that will drift. Confidence: high.\n\n## Approaches\n\n### 1. Persist ordinary `system` messages\n\nTempting, but wrong. The current context builder deliberately strips persisted system-role messages because AI SDK v6 rejects them in message history: [context-builder.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/api/src/chats/context-builder.ts:180). It would also contaminate exports, pagination, and compaction semantics.\n\nReject.\n\n### 2. Add a general `chat_context_events` timeline\n\nArchitecturally clean and extensible, but premature. It creates another paginated, RLS-protected event stream before llame has more than two relevant event types.\n\nDefer until model transitions, instruction reloads, memory changes, permissions, and similar events justify a general timeline.\n\n### 3. Run prompt receipt plus semantic message parts\n\nRecommended. Confidence: high.\n\n- The run references an immutable, content-addressed prompt snapshot.\n- Server-authored non-text message parts place transition UI beside the affected message.\n- The model context builder translates those semantic parts into provider-appropriate context.\n- Search continues indexing only visible user/assistant text.\n- Public sharing continues exporting only text.\n- No raw reminder string becomes chat content.\n\nThis fits llame’s existing AI SDK message-part design and avoids a parallel event system.\n\n## Architecture section: prompts and transitions\n\n### Per-model prompt profiles\n\nEach model must resolve to a complete prompt—not a shared template with `${modelName}` substituted.\n\n```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"system:openai:gpt-5.4\",\n  \"prompt\": {\n    \"profile\": \"llame:gpt-5.4:v1\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nA custom model can provide a complete inline prompt:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"id\": \"local:qwen3\",\n  \"prompt\": {\n    \"system\": \"You are llame...\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nRules:\n\n- Exactly one of `profile` or `system`.\n- Named built-in profiles are versioned, code-owned artifacts.\n- Inline prompts are instance configuration.\n- Two models may deliberately reference the same profile, but there is no implicit family inheritance.\n- Unknown models do not receive a guessed prompt based on their name.\n- A fallback target always resolves its own complete prompt.\n- The immutable llame runtime/security contract remains enforced in code; the configured prompt owns model behavior, not authorization.\n\nThis gives genuinely different prompts to models with different reasoning, tool-use, verbosity, or instruction-following characteristics.\n\n### Effective prompt receipt\n\nEach model attempt records:\n\n```text\nrequestedModelId\neffectiveModelId\npromptProfileId | inline\nsystemPromptHash\nfull system prompt\ntool ids\ntool-schema hash\ntransition reason\ncompiler version\n```\n\nRaw prompt text should be deduplicated through content-addressed snapshots rather than copied into every run. Users can inspect the exact snapshot through the run/message receipt.\n\nThe receipt should show tool names and descriptions separately from the system prompt. That makes provider input understandable without pretending tool schemas are system-prompt text.\n\n### Explicit model switch\n\nSelection is captured when the user sends the message. Changing the selector while generation is running affects the next message—it must not mutate the active run.\n\nTimeline:\n\n```text\nAssistant response from Model A\n\n──────── Model changed: A → B ────────\nUser message sent to Model B\n\nAssistant response from Model B\n```\n\nThe server adds a trusted non-text part to the triggering user message:\n\n```text\ndata-model-context-change\n  fromModelId\n  toModelId\n  promptChanged\n  promptSnapshotId\n  reason = user_selection\n```\n\nThe UI renders it immediately before the user bubble, like the existing compaction boundary. The context builder serializes a short reminder before that user’s content for Model B. Because the semantic part is retained, later context reconstruction remains deterministic.\n\nDo not store the literal `<system-reminder>` string. Store the typed event and render provider-specific text from it.\n\n### Automatic fallback\n\nFallback is discovered after the user message, so displaying it before that message would lie about causality.\n\n```text\nUser message sent requesting Model A\n\n──────── Fallback: A → B · unavailable ────────\nAssistant response from Model B\n```\n\nThe fallback model receives its own full system prompt plus a transient model-change context update before its attempt. The UI event is stored as a non-text part at the beginning of the resulting assistant message.\n\nFallback is allowed only before:\n\n- visible assistant output;\n- completed tool calls;\n- other externally observable effects.\n\nAfter any of those, fail the run transparently. Restarting with another model would risk mixed authorship or duplicate tool execution.\n\nUser-triggered live switching during inference should not be in this change. It requires abort/restart semantics, partial-output handling, and tool-side-effect boundaries. That is a separate feature, not a variation of the selector.\n\n### Search and sharing\n\nThe requirement is already structurally supported:\n\n- Search indexes only text parts from user/assistant messages: [conversation-chunker.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/api/src/search/chat/conversation-chunker.ts:13).\n- Existing tests explicitly exclude system/tool/non-text parts: [conversation-chunker.spec.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/api/src/search/chat/conversation-chunker.spec.ts:37).\n- Public sharing allowlists text parts from user/assistant messages: [chats.dto.ts](/home/leon0399/Projects/llame/apps/api/src/chats/dto/chats.dto.ts:530).\n\nTherefore:\n\n- Model-switch blocks are visible in the owner’s transcript.\n- They never enter lexical or future semantic chat search.\n- They are excluded from public sharing and text export.\n- Prompt receipts are owner-only operational metadata.\n- Search tests should include the actual rendered reminder text as a negative probe.\n\nDoes this architecture and lifecycle match your intent—particularly capturing model selection at send time and excluding user-triggered mid-inference switching from this change?\n\n<oai-mem-citation>\n<citation_entries>\nMEMORY.md:260-283|note=[confirmed current llame model catalog and selected model persistence baseline]\n</citation_entries>\n<rollout_ids>\n019f4371-f1a5-7922-838d-530f1bd20ec4\n</rollout_ids>\n</oai-mem-citation>",
